  "prompt": "What is the heavy feeling near the larynx which one feels when he or she is feeling guilty, sad or depressed?",
  "response": "The feeling you're describing is often referred to as a \"lump in the throat\" or \"globus sensation.\" In psychological terms, this is sometimes called \"globus hystericus\" or \"globus pharyngeus.\" It's a common physical manifestation of emotional distress, such as sadness, grief, or guilt.\n\nThis sensation occurs when emotional stress causes the muscles in the throat to tighten, creating a feeling of a physical obstruction or heaviness near the larynx, even though there is no actual physical blockage. It's a psychosomatic response where emotional turmoil is experienced as a physical sensation.\n\nThe feeling is often associated with suppressed emotions and can be a sign of psychological tension or unresolved emotional issues. While it can be uncomfortable, it is generally not a serious medical condition. However, if the sensation persists or is accompanied by other symptoms, it's always advisable to consult a healthcare professional.",
